## Frontend Development Directory
ALWAYS work in the `/frontend` folder when implementing frontend or design changes:
- Navigate to `frontend/` directory before making any UI/UX changes
- All frontend commands (npm, yarn, etc.) must be run from within the frontend directory
- Verify you're in the correct directory with `pwd` before starting frontend work
- The frontend directory contains: `pages/`, `components/`, `styles/`, `public/`, etc.

## Frontend Command Structure
When running frontend commands:
1. First navigate to frontend directory: `cd frontend`
2. Then run your frontend command
3. Example: `cd frontend && npm run dev`

## Frontend Project Structure
- Next.js application in `frontend/` directory
- Components in `frontend/components/`
- Pages in `frontend/pages/`
- Styles in `frontend/styles/`
- Public assets in `frontend/public/`
- Configuration files: `package.json`, `tailwind.config.ts`, `next.config.ts`

## Package Management
- Only install npm packages within the frontend directory
- Update package.json when adding new dependencies
- Use `npm install` or `yarn add` from within frontend directory

## Development Workflow
- Start development server: `cd frontend && npm run dev`
- Build for production: `cd frontend && npm run build`
- Install dependencies: `cd frontend && npm install`
- Run tests: `cd frontend && npm test`

## File Organization
- Keep all frontend-related files within the frontend directory
- Don't mix frontend and backend files
- Use proper imports relative to the frontend directory structure
